document.title: Ohio’s Learning Standards – Extended Social Studies

5E5840D5D50E4599A7659C965B90CEA9.description:
Environmental concerns, impacted by
population growth and heightened by international competition
for the world’s energy supplies, have resulted in a new
environmental consciousness and a movement for the
sustainability of the world’s resources.

69E2B75B61DB4ED38704781034CB623E.description:
Match
definitions to the terms
global population and life
expectancy

B07E715CA9544482B3A39A803B77281F.description:
Identify causes
of global societal challenges
(e.g., increased global
population, increased life
expectancy, mass migrations).

A41A5A17C9E846D39462062600A0B105.description:
Explain the
relationship between
increased life expectancy and
the global population.

1B58DFE8DB8147CF90A4CB1FCFD5EBDC.description:
The rapid increase of global population,
coupled with rising life expectancy and mass migrations, has
created societal and governmental challenges.

62519C6FF39944CA92776E07518443D7.description:
Identify a
country that has nuclear
weapons.

3AD9958410FC4F6187C02943BFB96677.description:
Identify
countries besides the United
States and Russia that have
nuclear weapons.

ED08DCB8FE8F4976819A0AE651328446.description:
Explain how
the proliferation of nuclear
weapons has created a
challenge to world peace.

B95C6E111CDC422EB93FF74A59BBA215.description:
Proliferation of nuclear weapons has created a
challenge to world peace.

44B063B1849A44D4BFCACA359E4224D6.description:
Explain how
an emerging economic power
or an improvement in
technology has created a
more interdependent global
economy.

0D89C20728FC4BCEB29E6E10882637F1.description:
Emerging economic powers and improvements
in technology have created a more interdependent global
economy.

6A8143013515457A9AE0BAAACEB18EF5.description:
Identify a
political or cultural group that
has struggled to achieve
self-governance.

30B0903D6D7C4291B36618AE5BA149AF.description:
Identify several
political and cultural groups
that have struggled to achieve
self-governance.

CD7E70D5FBF240D3A26B36E1F2E41CED.description:
Identify
several political groups that
struggled to achieve selfgovernance and describe their
struggles.

EDE027D40D624226A9D508F515239693.description:
Political and cultural groups have struggled to
achieve self-governance and self-determination.

0AA93736CB534AAFB8A981D54C2E63C5.description:
Define
terrorism, genocide and ethnic
cleansing.

6FB2FD31B6994094B9BC14E50A9BF1D2.description:
Link a post–
Cold War act of terrorism,
genocide or ethnic cleansing
with a regional or ethnic
conflict.

911E7F70FEBA49D5B521F74DFF13DE25.description:
Regional and ethnic conflicts in the post–Cold
War era have resulted in acts of terrorism, genocide and
ethnic cleansing.

8A2D05AE670844F69B156B2CD72FD4BE.description:
Identify a
country that formerly
belonged to the Soviet
Union.

F27D073E85A440F8B2D77BBB4832740C.description:
List multiple
countries that formerly
belonged to the Soviet Union.

AD7F97C6992E4097952B4947EE2B95ED.description:
Describe an
impact resulting from the
breakup of the Soviet Union.

C789F6C59CF04D6CAFA5C21B23F173F5.description:
The breakup of the Soviet Union ended the
Cold War and created challenges for its former allies, the
former Soviet republics, Europe, the United States and the
non-aligned world.

B9F49591D6BA4E4789806D0B2B7D2A93.description:
Identify a
group who fought for
expanded rights and
freedoms (e.g., women or
indigenous groups, such as
Aboriginal Australians,
Native Africans, American
Indians).

9A65C27344374CEAB23DFF5F370AEE68.description:
Match political
and/or social struggles with
the resulting expanded rights
and/or freedoms for women
and/or indigenous peoples.

B1DC3D70034941869227003AAA8F5229.description:
Political and social struggles have resulted in
expanded rights and freedoms for women and indigenous
peoples.

F6376D3C1A6D4CB98A5ACBCCC8676286.description:
Identify a
country that experienced a
nationalist movement
following World War II.

877B4D360A6F4B0E85C5E16282C71267.description:
Research and
summarize a nationalist
movement in Africa or
Southeast Asia.

62553A088E984A7A989A28E94BFD722D.description:
Postwar global politics led to the rise of
nationalist movements in Africa and Southeast Asia.

9568385027EE4433ABC602B504899AB1.description:
Identify a
country in the Middle East.

87B6E0C4763E4C70BC0DDAA1E914F8DA.description:
Identify
countries that have been
involved in historic regional
conflicts in the Middle East.

EA7656FD5E904A808779B5DEB0D060B4.description:
Explain
causes of historic regional
conflicts in the Middle East.

3A987D4ABADF46E7913A1F9468B2267E.description:
Religious diversity, the end of colonial rule and
rising nationalism have led to regional conflicts in the Middle
East.

2F4F5A81204A447EB4C11BA02086ADA8.description:
Identify the
purpose of a treaty.

71E95D0816CA48F9B2B950DBCBE107B5.description:
Explain what
the United Nations does.

16E90FD239CA49B98124C36E0B38122E.description:
Explain how
World War II contributed to the
creation of East and West
Germany.

FE2C4F4F191B46988ABB264526559B8D.description:
Treaties and agreements at the end of World
War II changed national boundaries and created multinational
organizations.

73DAE50D0071485FB8C5A9A111DE9ABD.description:
Identify the
United States and Soviet
Union (or Russia) on a globe
or map.

EDF4794169F54B11B50A7E1E619BCB09.description:
Describe the
relationship between the
United States and the Soviet
Union in the decades following
World War II (e.g., the Cold
War)

E333BC4E71F64B25BF54F002BF39F7B7.description:
Explain key
differences between the
United States and the Soviet
Union in the decades following
World War II (e.g.,
government and economic
systems)

4681999C0D43418DB892E1C3B1FDB1A3.description:
The United States and the Soviet Union
became superpowers and competed for global influence.

A2EA587412704C3EBBDADCEAF9D871F8.description:
Identify an
area that was occupied after
World War II.

9EEF97CE756F47119CD5FCB7F1AD58C1.description:
Identify
countries that occupied
Eastern Europe and Japan.

827DF8AA718149BF88C6F5426BED277B.description:
Identify
reasons for post–WWII
territorial occupation of
Eastern Europe.

E6A620EB10624FC59204220F24476141.description:
World War II devastated most of Europe and
Asia, led to the occupation of Eastern Europe and Japan, and
began the atomic age.

A481072F33814AE4BFE90ADF78C77AB6.description:
Identify an
example of oppression
during World War II.

880D0DE2B951415AA82C58D2BE57A959.description:
Provide
examples of oppression during
World War II.

8854D58E933F41C08F32739FF0C9532F.description:
Explain how
oppression and discrimination
resulted in the Armenian
Genocide during World War I
and the Holocaust during
World War II.

43C1419DF3B74588A78F274BB12C4C45.description:
Oppression and discrimination resulted in the
Armenian Genocide during World War I and the Holocaust
during World War II.

F42CB8C58F18416FBC28CECAFC742EDC.description:
Identify one
consequence of World War I.

D37CC1D5483243D5933DCCC9522EF2F1.description:
Describe three
causes of World War II (e.g.,
the Russian Revolution,
totalitarianism, aggressive
Axis expansion,
appeasement).

356483E257BB414FA7178182528DD305.description:
The consequences of World War I and the
worldwide depression set the stage for the Russian
Revolution, the rise of totalitarianism, aggressive Axis
expansion and the policy of appeasement, which in turn led to
World War II.

1C4050C6C9B349BBA24078666AD6A6FB.description:
Identify the
meaning of war (e.g., two
countries fighting with each
another).

25326F5E20894B408391E466638EB071.description:
Identify the
main causes of World War I
(i.e., militarism, imperialism,
nationalism and alliances).

283131BFB9714E0E9858BB8052C18D4A.description:
Describe the
main causes of World War I
(i.e., militarism, imperialism,
nationalism and alliances).

0B7AA5A77AF94846A397C109AD349241.description:
The causes of World War I included militarism,
imperialism, nationalism and alliances.

87A3527D5438415E8EEE300CDB12508E.description:
Identify an
advancement in technology,
communication or
transportation during the
early 20th century.

4B1E68E3DC0840B69350F1214B04FC3E.description:
List several
advancements in technology
during the early 20th century.

BF0D1CE05A9E4C02A03040F37866FF6F.description:
Describe a
positive and a negative impact
of advancements in
technology, communication or
transportation during the early
20th century.

44734007879B4E67A13DFA9921860CF9.description:
Advances in technology, communication and
transportation improved lives but also had negative
consequences.

9838EC220F98474ABB86C397E4716AD7.description:
Identify a
colonizing region and a
colonized region.

331856AE55784A46A2670879CAC1496B.description:
Determine
whether a given historical
document from the Imperialist
era was written by the
colonizers or the colonized.

3C11D7ECAE4643B78D04484703635800.description:
Provide one
example of how Imperialism
was viewed by the colonizers
and the colonized.

D045068F2FD7473FBC51F988D491A419.description:
The consequences of Imperialism were viewed
differently by the colonizers and the colonized.

000317CA98CD40B38BCC293187BB3E41.description:
Categorize
examples of land acquisition,
extraction of raw materials,
spread of Western values, and
direct political control (e.g.,
missionaries, rubber
acquisition).

E6BFB6DC5A90411B8974CAF214DCC362.description:
Give
examples of land acquisition,
extraction of raw materials,
spread of Western values, and
direct political control (e.g.,
missionaries, rubber
acquisition).

373D43B33B7C438B963220CB022F91F2.description:
Imperialism involved land acquisition,
extraction of raw materials, spread of Western values and
direct political control.

71A211E1C019489BB54C2AD9798C1470.description:
Identify a
reason for Imperial expansion.

CB5E1EAE1DD341B9BD87B078F25C2E51.description:
Describe
political, economic and social
reasons for Imperial
expansion.

2BDE61D856EB402EAA625739164E559D.description:
Imperial expansion had political, economic and
social roots.

26F4992CF1924F49AF9E2ED4E7FA793B.description:
Describe one
social, political or economic
impact of industrialization on
Western Europe.

0CC7B3ED68334704B4138A9C6C4EAF2A.description:
Industrialization had social, political and
economic effects on Western Europe and the world.

BD7EF3CAF2054284B4665EC17333B5F8.description:
Identify a
Latin American country that
experienced a political
revolution as a result of the
American and French
revolutions.

D33146D810834DB29C1CE730968BA001.description:
Explain
similarities between the
American and French
revolutions.

EF5DE0F31C374E6B84F66835B153BDEB.description:
The American and French Revolutions
influenced Latin American revolutions for independence.

39F18E8B9457423E8D80316543C06EFB.description:
Identify one of
the Rights of Man.

4B81C310562E4AD185EFDEEB3343FFDE.description:
Identify how
individual rights changed after
the American Revolution.

AAF4E0FE33FC410A89BFC071747BEC1D.description:
Enlightenment ideas on the relationship of the
individual and the government influenced the American and
French Revolutions.

97D3DD1D57C44F4485E7D40EE029F937.description:
Distinguish
between the Enlightenment
and other major historical
periods (e.g., the Industrial
Revolution, the Cold War).

56685AB81DE74E50A056AF99050338D2.description:
Describe how
one major Enlightenment idea
challenged traditional ways of
thinking.

424223986459418AA1FBCD317AA812AE.description:
Enlightenment ideas regarding human nature
and society challenged religious authority, absolute rule and
mercantilism.

26D8163D3303469AA25D0D82DB6A0C93.description:
Identify one
major individual, idea or
invention from the Scientific
Revolution.

DCEE09236DB34838906336E715EE2F5D.description:
Describe an old
idea that was challenged or
disproven during the Scientific
Revolution.

34A155DFD8F344179FD596E8DC58C1AE.description:
Explain how
new ideas from the Scientific
Revolution changed existing
governments and religious
institutions.

CBD686FF65E84564ABE94704A1D8FFE5.description:
The Scientific Revolution impacted religious,
political and cultural institutions by challenging how people
viewed the world.

1B54010AE1144118A351703781AB058F.description:
Identify a
historical event occurring
before or after another given
event.

DC864AC1273545728DE24F804EE48997.description:
Identify the
cause and result of a given
historical event.

40E415B2F00F443F891626E67268DED7.description:
Describe the
cause or result of a historical
event and a possible alternate
course of action.

0FCDBAD1C1114424BCD83CBD546E32E8.description:
Historians analyze cause, effect, sequence and
correlation in historical events, including multiple causation
and long- and short-term causal relations.

01D7F384CF064088870E27915E0093F8.description:
Match
evidence with the thesis it
supports.

444320CAB0534F0D80BE6DFBEA6F6479.description:
Identify a piece
of evidence that supports a
given thesis.

28FC4737BA5641F7AF069A4B1AEB31B2.description:
Develop a
thesis to support or refute a
position.

005D1AFE0F0942D8A4C2F1EBF9A2B489.description:
Historians develop theses and use evidence to
support or refute positions.

02305E73569A47B592C71EFD4C270646.description:
Distinguish
between a primary and
secondary source.

11DF95B729904C089F024933D7DB66F4.description:
Identify a
credible source of information.

8236A383B3014E2F8B520AC4E24D367E.description:
Explain the
difference between a primary
and secondary source.

34B7AE7063B84D2BB8EABC2C7C800183.description:
The use of primary and secondary sources of
information includes an examination of the credibility of each
source.
